{
  "genre": "latin",
  "mode": "focus",
  "mixStrategy": "This Latin/Salsa focus arrangement uses the Andalusian cadence (Am \u2192 G \u2192 F \u2192 E7) cycling every 6.4 seconds (8 beats at 75 BPM). All four tracks lock to a 3-2 son clave grid. FREQUENCY SEPARATION: Bass (Electric Bass, MIDI 33-45) fills 20-300Hz with a tumbao pattern \u2014 syncopated roots and fifths anticipating beat 4 and beat 1, providing the rhythmic-harmonic foundation. Piano montuno (MIDI 48-67) fills 300Hz-2kHz with repetitive arpeggiated chord voicings that interlock with the clave, creating the harmonic body. Flute melody (MIDI 65-81) fills 1-8kHz with lyrical, syncopated phrases using chord tones on strong beats and scalar passing tones on weak beats \u2014 the most prominent voice but kept at moderate velocity (55-75) for focus mode. Drums fill the rhythmic spectrum with son clave on sidestick, congas providing the tumbao accent pattern, and a light kick on beats 1 and 3 \u2014 all at restrained velocity for habituation. RHYTHMIC INTERLOCK: The bass anticipates where the kick lands, the piano montuno fills the spaces between clave hits, and the flute breathes in the gaps left by the montuno. ENERGY ARC: Segments 1-6 follow 0.4\u21920.6\u21920.7\u21920.7\u21920.7\u21920.5 \u2014 the piece starts sparse (bass+light drums), adds piano montuno in segment 2, flute enters in segment 3, sustains through segments 4-5, then the flute and drums thin out in segment 6 for a gentle wind-down. Chord changes happen every 1.6s (2 beats): Am for 2 beats, G for 2 beats, F for 2 beats, E7 for 2 beats, then repeat. All tracks change harmony together on the same beats.",
